<section xml:id="sec_logic_connectives">
  <title>Logical Connectives</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we introduce the logical connectives for
      <q>and</q>
      and
      <q>or</q>
      along with their proof formats.
      We discuss logical equivalence and negation and use truth tables to define connectives and verify equivalences.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let's warm up our logical thinking by considering some true/false questions.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_TorF">
      <title>True or false?</title>
      <p>
        Decide if each statement is true or false and discuss how to justify your answer.
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_digit_sum23">
            <p>
              There are three distinct digits whose sum is 23.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_digit_sum25">
            <p>
              There are three distinct digits whose sum is 25.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_pos_or_neg">
            <p>
              Every integer is positive or negative.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_div3_and_div5">
            <p>
              Some integers are divisible by three and five.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_div6_but_ndiv3">
            <p>
              Some integers are divisible by six but not by three.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_graph_order5">
            <p>
              A graph with five vertices is the cycle <m>C_5</m> or the complete graph <m>K_5</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every graph is a tree, which means that it is connected and acyclic.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every bit string of length five begins or ends with <c>0</c>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_bs5_three0_or_three1">
            <p>
              Every bit string of length five has at least three <c>0</c> s or at least three <c>1</c> s.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_and_or">
    <title>\subandor</title>
    <p>
      <xref ref="act_TorF">In</xref>,
      there are many words that indicate the logical structure of a statement.
      Two important such words are
      <q>and</q>
      and
      <q>or</q>, each of which has a specific technical meaning in mathematics and computer science.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_and_or_xor">
      <title>And, or, and xor</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                A <term>statement</term> is a sentence that is either true or false.
                For example,
                <m>P=</m> the integer six has exactly four positive divisors. is a statement that happens to be true because the positive divisors of six are 1, 2, 3, and 6.
                The statement <m>Q=</m> the cycle <m>C_5</m> has a vertex of degree three. is false because all the vertices of <m>C_5</m> have degree two.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, the statement
                <q><m>P</m> <term>and</term> <m>Q</m></q>, denoted <m>P \land Q</m>,
                is true if both <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are true and false otherwise.
                For example,
                the statement The integer seven is positive and odd. is true because seven is positive and seven is odd.
                The statement The integer six is positive and odd. is false,
                even though six is positive because six is not odd.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, the statement
                <q><m>P</m> <term>or</term> <m>Q</m></q>, denoted <m>P \lor Q</m>,
                is true if at least one of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are true and false otherwise.
                For example,
                the statement The integer six is positive or odd. is true,
                because six is positive.
                The statement A graph with five vertices is either the cycle <m>C_5</m> or the complete graph <m>K_5</m>. from <xref ref="act_TorF"></xref>
                <xref ref="part_graph_order5"/> is false because, for example,
                the graph <m>P_5</m> has five vertices but it is not a cycle and it is not complete.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Note that <m>P \lor Q</m> is true if both <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are true.
                For example,
                the statement The integer seven is positive or odd. is true.
                This use of
                <q>or</q>
                is the <term>inclusive or</term> because it includes the possibility of both statements being true.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                When we want to exclude the possibility of both statements being true,
                we use the <term>exclusive or</term> instead.
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, the statement
                <q><m>P</m> <term>xor</term> <m>Q</m></q>, denoted <m>P \oplus Q</m>,
                is true if one of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> is true and the other is false and false otherwise.
                For example, when I told my kids
                <q>you can have ice cream or brownies for dessert</q>
                they suggested brownies with ice cream
                (the inclusive or),
                but I probably meant one or the other but not both
                (the exclusive or).
                As another example,
                in <xref ref="exam_every_integer_even_or_odd"></xref>
                we showed that Every integer is either even or odd,
                but never both. which we could write more concisely as Every integer is even xor odd.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                One way to summarize when a compound statement is true or false is to use a <term>truth table</term>
                which includes a column for each component of the compound statement
                (such as <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>)
                and for the full compound statement
                (such as <m>P \land Q</m>)
                and a row for each possible combination of true or false for the component statements.
                For example, if our components are <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
                then the truth table will have four rows corresponding to the four possibilities:
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q</m> is true;
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q</m> is false;
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>P</m> is false and <m>Q</m> is true; and
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      <m>P</m> is false and <m>Q</m> is false.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </p>
              In this textbook we abbreviate true as <c>T</c> and false as <c>F</c>.
              Some computer science textbooks use <c>1</c> for true and <c>0</c> for false instead.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We show the truth tables for the compound statements <m>P \land Q</m>,
      <m>P \lor Q</m>, and <m>P \oplus Q</m> in our next example.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_truthtable_and_or_xor">
      <title>Truth tables for and, or, and xor</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use a truth table to illustrate the meaning of the logical connective <m>\land</m>
                (and).
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_and"></xref>
                    shows the truth table for <m>P \land Q</m>.
                    Since the only time <m>P \land Q</m> is true is when both <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> are true,
                    the only <c>T</c> in the
                    <m>P \land Q</m> column is in the first row.
                    The other entries in the <m>P \land Q</m> column are all <c>F</c>.
                  </p>
                  <table xml:id="table_truthtable_and">
                    <title>Truth table for the logical connective <term>and</term></title>
                    <tabular>
                      <row>
                        <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>P \land Q</m></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                    </tabular>
                  </table>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use a truth table to illustrate the meaning of the logical connective <m>\lor</m>
                (or).
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_or"></xref>
                    shows the truth table for <m>P \lor Q</m>.
                    Since <m>P \lor Q</m> is true is whenever <m>P</m> is true,
                    the first two entries in the
                    <m>P \land Q</m> column are <c>T</c>.
                    Since <m>P \lor Q</m> is true whenever <m>Q</m> is true,
                    the third entry in the <m>P \land Q</m> column is also <c>T</c>.
                    The final entry in the <m>P \land Q</m> column is <c>F</c> because neither <m>P</m> nor <m>Q</m> are true.
                  </p>
                  <table xml:id="table_truthtable_or">
                    <title>Truth table for the logical connective <term>or</term></title>
                    <tabular>
                      <row>
                        <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                    </tabular>
                  </table>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use a truth table to illustrate the meaning of the logical connective <m>\oplus</m>
                (xor).
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_xor"></xref>
                    shows the truth table for <m>P \oplus Q</m>.
                    Since <m>P \oplus Q</m> is true exactly when one of <m>P</m> or <m>Q</m> is true,
                    the <m>P \oplus Q</m> column has <c>T</c> in the second and third rows only.
                  </p>
                  <table xml:id="table_truthtable_xor">
                    <title>Truth table for the logical connective <term>xor</term></title>
                    <tabular>
                      <row>
                        <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>P \oplus Q</m></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                    </tabular>
                  </table>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is your turn to create a truth table.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_truthtable_and_or">
      <title>Truth tables with and and or</title>
      <p>
        <xref ref="table_truthtable_and_or"></xref>
        shows the beginning of the truth table for the compound statement <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m>.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table_truthtable_and_or">
        <title>Part of the truth table for <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m></title>
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell><m>P</m></cell>
            <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>R</m></cell>
            <cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row bottom="minor">
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
            <cell></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            According to the truth table in <xref ref="table_truthtable_and_or"></xref>,
            when <m>P</m> is true,
            <m>Q</m> is false, and <m>R</m> is true, which row are we in
            (do not count the
            <q>header row</q>
            with <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, etc.)
            and is the statement <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m> true or false?
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            We are missing the last couple of rows of <xref ref="table_truthtable_and_or"></xref>.
            What are the remaining true/false options?
            Fill in the <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>,
            and <m>R</m> columns for the missing rows.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <xref ref="table_truthtable_and_or">In</xref>
            we included an intermediate column for <m>P \lor Q</m>.
            Convince yourself that we correctly started that column and complete it.
            Notice that we ignore the <m>R</m> column.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="part_finish_truthtable">
          <p>
            Convince yourself that we correctly started the final column for
            <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m> in <xref ref="table_truthtable_and_or"></xref> and complete it.
            Notice that we need to look at only the column for <m>R</m> and the intermediate column for <m>P \lor Q</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Construct a new truth table for the compound statement <m>(P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)</m>.
            Include intermediate columns for
            <m>P \land R</m> and for <m>Q \land R</m>.
            What do you notice?
            Hint: Compare to <xref ref="table_truthtable_and_or"></xref>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If we wanted to construct a truth table for a compound statement involving four components (<m>P</m>,
            <m>Q</m>,
            <m>R</m>, and <m>S</m>), how many rows would it need.
            Explain how you counted.
            Hint: Steps.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Make sure that you have <xref ref="act_truthtable_and_or">completed</xref>
      because we are going to reveal some of the answers.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_distributive_equiv">
      <title>Distributive rule</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use a truth table to verify the logical equivalence
          <me>
            (P \lor Q) \land R \equiv (P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The truth table is in <xref ref="table_truthtable_distrib"></xref>.
          Notice that the columns for <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m> and for
          <m>(P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)</m> have the same sequence of <c>T</c> s and <c>F</c> s.
        </p>
        <table xml:id="table_truthtable_distrib">
          <title>A truth table verifying the distributive equivalence <m>(P \lor Q) \land R \equiv (P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)</m></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>P</m></cell>
              <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
              <cell><m>R</m></cell>
              <cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m></cell>
              <cell><m>P \land R</m></cell>
              <cell><m>Q \land R</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_and_or">
    <title>\subpffandor</title>
    <p>
      How can we prove statements involving and and or?
      To prove <m>P \land Q</m>, we need to prove two things:
      <m>P</m> and then <m>Q</m>.
      We can summarize this idea in a proof format.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>P \land Q</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        First, (explain why <m>P</m> is true.) Therefore, <m>P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Next, (explain why <m>Q</m> is true.) Therefore, <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      The format for a proof of <m>P \lor Q</m> is less direct.
      An option is to use a modified version of a proof by cases.
      Later in this textbook, we introduce two other options:
      proof by contradiction in <xref ref="sub_pff_contra"></xref>
      and proof using the equivalent conditional in <xref ref="sub_pff_if_then"></xref>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <xref ref="sub_pff_cases">In</xref> we introduced proof by cases.
      In each case of the format in <xref ref="pff_cases"></xref>,
      we proved the same statement.
      We can modify that proof format to prove
      <m>P \lor Q</m> by proving <m>P</m> in one case and <m>Q</m> in the other case.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>P \lor Q</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        (Explain why there are two cases.) We consider two cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        Case 1: Assume <ellipsis/>.
        (Explain why <m>P</m> is true in this case.)
        Therefore, <m>P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Case 2: Assume <ellipsis/>.
        (Explain why <m>Q</m> is true in this case.)
        Therefore, <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In either case, we have <m>P \lor Q</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      We present this format with two cases,
      since that is often all we need.
      This format can be modified to have more than two cases where in some cases <m>P</m> is true and in other cases <m>Q</m> is true.
      Officially, this is a new proof format.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>P_1 \lor P_2 \lor \cdots \lor P_k</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        (Explain why there are <m>n</m> cases.) We consider <m>n</m> cases.
      </p>
      <p>
        Case 1: Assume <ellipsis/> (Explain why one of
        <m>P_1, P_2, \ldots P_k</m> is true in this case.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Case 2: Assume <ellipsis/> (Explain why one of
        <m>P_1, P_2, \ldots P_k</m> is true in this case.)
      </p>
      <p>
        <ellipsis/>
      </p>
      <p>
        Case <m>n</m>: Assume <ellipsis/> (Explain why one of
        <m>P_1, P_2, \ldots P_k</m> is true in this case.)
      </p>
      <p>
        In (either case/all cases) we have <m>P_1 \lor P_2 \lor \cdots \lor P_k</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Try working with these formats.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_prove_and_orusingcases">
      <title>Proving <m>\land</m> and <m>\lor</m> by using cases</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_pff_and_example">
            <p>
              Copy the following example of a proof of an
              <q>and</q>
              statement.
              Prove that 30 is even and <m>5 \mid 30</m>.
              <proof>
                <p>
                  First, <m>30 = 2(15)=2k</m> when <m>k=15</m> and so 30 is even.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Next, <m>30 = 5(6) = 5k</m> when <m>k=6</m> and so <m>5 \mid 30</m>.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_pff_and_example"/> to prove that 33 is odd and <m>3 \mid 33</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_pff_or_using_cases_example">
            <p>
              Copy the following example of a proof of an
              <q>or</q>
              statement using cases.
              Prove that <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 4 = 0</m> or
              <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 4 = 1</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
              Yes, this proof <xref ref="exer_proof_cases_square_mod4">was</xref>
              in <xref ref="sec_div_alg"></xref>.
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
                  Then <m>n</m> is either even or odd,
                  by <xref ref="exam_every_integer_even_or_odd"></xref>.
                  We consider two cases.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Case 1: Assume that <m>n</m> is even.
                  By the definition of even,
                  we can write <m>n = 2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                  Then
                  <me>
                    n^2=(2k)^2=4k^2=4(k^2) = 4q=4q+0
                  </me>
                  where <m>q=k^2</m> is an integer.
                  Therefore, <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 4 = 0</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Case 2: Assume that <m>n</m> is odd.
                  By the definition of odd,
                  we can write <m>n = 2k+1</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                  Then
                  <me>
                    n^2=(2k+1)^2 = (2k+1)(2k+1)=4k^2+4k+1 = 4(k^2+k) + 1 = 4q+1
                  </me>
                  where <m>q =k^2+k</m> is an integer.
                  Therefore, <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 4 = 1</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  In either case,
                  we have <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 4 = 0</m> or <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 4 = 1</m>.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_nsqplusn_mod4">
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_pff_or_using_cases_example"/> to prove that <m>n^2+2n \fn{ mod } 4 = 0</m> or
              <m>n^2+2n \fn{ mod } 4 = 3</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_logical_equivalence_negations">
    <title>\subequivneg</title>
    <p>
      <xref ref="act_truthtable_and_or">In</xref>,
      we saw that the statements <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m> and
      <m>(P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)</m> have the same final column in their truth table.
      That is, in each case
      (row of the truth table),
      they are both true or both false.
      We have a name for the situation where two logical statements have the same truth values.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_logical_equiv">
      <title>Logical equivalence</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_equiv_distributive">
              <p>
                Statements <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> are
                <term>logically equivalent</term>,
                denoted <m>S \equiv T</m>,
                if <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> always have the same truth value,
                either both statements are true or both statements are false.
                For example,
                we saw in <xref ref="act_truthtable_and_or"></xref> that
                <me>
                  (P \lor Q) \land R \equiv (P \land R) \lor (Q \land R)
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Statements <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> are
                <term>not logically equivalent</term>,
                denoted <m>S \not \equiv T</m> if sometimes one of the statements is true but the other is false.
                For example,
                <me>
                  (P \lor Q) \land R \not \equiv P \lor (Q \land R)
                </me>
                as we check in <xref ref="exer_not_assoc"></xref> because,
                for example,
                when <m>P</m> is true and both <m>Q</m> and <m>R</m> are false,
                the left-hand side <m>(P \lor Q) \land R</m> is false but the right-hand side <m>P \lor (Q \land R)</m> is true.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Logically equivalent statements always have the same truth values.
      There is also a name for when two statements always have the opposite truth value as well as names for logical statements that are always true or always false.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_negation_tautology_contradiction">
      <title>Negation, tautology, and contradiction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The statements <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> are <term>negations</term>
                if <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> always have the opposite truth value.
                That is, <m>S</m> is true and <m>T</m> is false or <m>S</m> is false and <m>T</m> is true.
                The statement <m>T</m> is the <term>negation</term>
                of <m>S</m>, denoted <m>\neg S</m>.
                For example,
                if <m>n</m> is an integer and if <m>S</m> is the statement <m>n >2</m>,
                then <m>\neg S</m> is the statement <m>n \le 2</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A statement <m>S</m> is a <term>tautology</term> if it is always true.
                For example,
                the statement Either I will work on my homework Tuesday night or I will not work on my homework Tuesday night. is a tautology.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A statement <m>S</m> is a <term>contradiction</term> if it is always false.
                For example,
                the statement There is an integer <m>n</m> with <m>n>2</m> and
                <m>n^2\lt 4</m>. is a contradiction because for an integer <m>n</m> with <m>n>2</m> we know that <m>n^2 > 4</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Here are examples of truth tables involving negations.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_truthtable_negations">
      <title>Truth tables involving negations</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use a truth table to illustrate the meaning of the logical operation <m>\neg</m>
                (not).
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_not"></xref>
                    shows the truth table for <m>\neg P</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_not">
                  <title>Truth table for the logical operation <term>not</term></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg P</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Construct a truth table for the compound statement <m>P \land \neg Q</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_andnot"></xref>
                    shows the truth table for <m>P \land \neg Q</m>,
                    using an intermediate column for <m>\neg Q</m>.
                    Notice that the only time <m>P \land \neg Q</m> is true is when <m>P</m> is true and <m>Q</m> is false,
                    which happens in the second row.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_andnot">
                  <title>Truth table for the compound statement <m>P \land \neg Q</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg Q</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \land \neg Q</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use a truth table to show that <m>P \land \neg P</m> is a contradiction.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_contradiction"></xref>
                    shows the truth table for <m>P \land \neg P</m>.
                    Since the final column is all <c>F</c>,
                    it follows that <m>P \land \neg P</m> is a contradiction.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="table_truthtable_contradiction">
                  <title>Truth table for the contradiction <m>P \land \neg P</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>\neg P</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>P \land \neg P</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      By the way, when the statement following the logical connective
      <q>and</q>
      is negative, we use the connective
      <q>but</q>
      instead.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_but_not">
      <title>But not</title>
      <p>
        It is common in English to pronounce <m>P \land \neg Q</m> as
        <q><m>P</m> but not <m>Q</m></q>. The word
        <q>but</q>
        has the same meaning logically as
        <q>and</q>
        but in English it indicates that what follows is negative in some way.
        For example,
        while we can say I like chocolate ice cream and I don't want any now. it is more common to say I like chocolate ice cream but I don't want any now.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Try your hand at working with negations.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_not_and">
      <title>Negating and</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <xref ref="defn_and_or_xor">In</xref>,
              we noted that the statement The integer seven is positive and odd. is true.
              Consider the general statement The integer <m>n</m> is positive and odd.
              Give examples of integers <m>n</m> where the statement is false,
              including some negative values of <m>n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_positive_and_odd">
            <p>
              For the statement The integer <m>n</m> is positive and odd. to be false,
              what needs to be true for <m>n</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_truth_not_and">
            <p>
              Construct a truth table for
              <m>\neg(P \land Q)</m> and <m>\neg P \land \neg Q</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Look at your truth table from <xref ref="part_truth_not_and"/>.
              Is <m>\neg(P \land Q) \equiv \neg P \land \neg Q</m>?
              Explain.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Is <m>\neg P \land \neg Q</m> the negation of <m>P \land Q</m>?
              Explain.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_conj_not_and">
            <p>
              Make a conjecture about the negation of <m>P \land Q</m>.
              Your answer should agree with your answer to <xref ref="part_positive_and_odd"/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Verify your conjecture from <xref ref="part_conj_not_and"/> using a truth table.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      <xref ref="act_not_and">In</xref>,
      we saw that the negation of
      <m>P \land Q</m> is not <m>\neg P \land \neg Q</m>.
      For <m>P \land Q</m> to be false,
      we need either <m>P</m> is false or <m>Q</m> is false or both are false.
      That is, we need <m>\neg P \lor \neg Q</m> to be true.
      Similarly, for <m>P \lor Q</m> to be false,
      we need both <m>P</m> is false and <m>Q</m> is false.
      That is, we need <m>\neg P \land \neg Q</m> to be true.
      We summarize these negations in a theorem.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_demorgans">
      <title>De Morgan's Law</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
          the negation of <m>P \land Q</m> is <m>\neg P \lor \neg Q</m> and the negation of
          <m>P \lor Q</m> is <m>\neg P \land \neg Q</m>.
          That is, we have the following logical equivalences known as
          <term>De Morgan's Laws</term>:
          <me>
            \neg(P \land Q) \equiv \neg P \lor \neg Q\text{ and } \neg(P \lor Q) \equiv \neg P \land \neg Q
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_contra">
    <title>\subpffcontra</title>
    <p>
      One method of proving that the statement <m>P</m> is true is to show that the assumption that <m>P</m> is false leads to a contradiction,
      such as a statement of the form <m>Q \land \neg Q</m>.
      That is, in a proof by contradiction of a statement <m>P</m>,
      we assume that <m>P</m> is false and deduce that both <m>Q</m> and <m>\neg Q</m> are true for some statement <m>Q</m>,
      which is impossible.
      That impossibility tells us that <m>P</m> cannot be false,
      and so <m>P</m> must be true.
    </p>
    <p>
      As we start writing a proof by contradiction,
      we usually do not know what the statement <m>Q</m> will be.
      Sometimes it helps to do a little scratch work listing the consequences of <m>P</m> being false to see if we find contradictory statements <m>Q</m> and <m>\neg Q</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <term>proof by contradiction</term>
      follows the following proof format.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: P
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose not.
        Then
        (state <m>\neg P</m>).
      </p>
      <p>
        First, (explain why <m>Q</m> is true.) Therefore, <m>Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the other hand,
        (explain why <m>\neg Q</m> is true.)
        Therefore, <m>\neg Q</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a contradiction.
        Therefore, <m>P</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      Notice that we are proving two things (<m>Q</m> and <m>\neg Q</m>),
      but instead of saying
      <q>First, <ellipsis/>.
      Next, ldots.</q>
      as we did in <xref ref="pff_and"></xref>, we use the expression
      <q>First, <ellipsis/>.
      On the other hand, ldots.</q>
      The phrase ``on the other hand`` alerts the reader that we are changing direction towards the negation of what we just proved.
      It is also acceptable to write ``On the one hand, <ellipsis/>.
      On the other hand, <ellipsis/>."
    </p>
    <p>
      Try writing a proof using contradiction.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_proof_contradiction">
      <title>Proof by contradiction: consecutive integers are coprime</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_contradiction_consec_coprime">
            <p>
              Copy the following example of a proof by contradiction.
              Prove <m>\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)=1</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.<fn>
              We proved this result in <xref ref="exer_consec_coprime"></xref>
              using the Euclidean Algorithm.
              </fn>
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Suppose not.
                  Then there exists an integer <m>n</m> such that <m>d=\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)\neq 1</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  First, by the definition of the greatest common divisor <xref ref="defn_gcd"/>,
                  <m>d \mid n</m> and <m>d \mid n+1</m>.
                  By the definition of divides <xref ref="defn_divides"/> we can write <m>n = dk_1</m> and
                  <m>n+1 = dk_2</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
                  Observe that
                  <me>
                    (n+1) - n = dk_2 - dk_1 = d(k_2-k_1)=dq
                  </me>
                  where <m>q = k_2-k_1</m> and so <m>d \mid (n+1)-n</m>.
                  But, of course, <m>(n+1)-n=1</m> so really <m>d \mid 1</m>.
                  Since the only positive divisor of 1 is 1, it follows that <m>d =1</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  On the other hand, we assumed that <m>d \neq 1</m>.
                  This is a contradiction.
                  Thus, <m>\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)=1</m>.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_contradiction_consec_coprime"/> to prove that
              <m>\fn{gcd}(n,n-1) = 1</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
              (Yes, we are again proving that consecutive integers are coprime.)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      There is a bit of controversy over the use of proof by contradiction.
      Some mathematicians dislike contradiction proofs because they do not actually show why a statement is true,
      only why it cannot be false.
      Other mathematicians like contradiction proofs because they settle an argument:
      if your reader thinks the statement is false,
      your proof shows them that something terrible goes wrong (a contradiction).
      We will let you decide which type of mathematician you are.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because of this controversy,
      we often rewrite a proof by contradiction using some other format,
      if possible.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_avoid_contradiction_consec_coprime">
      <title>Rewriting without contradiction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Copy the proof by contradiction from <xref ref="act_proof_contradiction"></xref>
          <xref ref="part_contradiction_consec_coprime"/> and edit to to give a proof without contradiction.
        </p>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)=1</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We have crossed out the statements that should be deleted,
          and boldfaced the statements that should be added.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Proof.</em> \st{Suppose not.
          Then there exists an integer <m>n</m> such that <m>d=\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)\neq 1</m>}
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Let <m>n</m> be an integer.
          Write <m>d=\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)</m>.
          Since 1 is a common divisor of any integer,
          <m>d</m> is certainly positive.</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          First, by the definition of greatest common divisor <xref ref="defn_gcd"/>,
          <m>d \mid n</m> and <m>d \mid n+1</m>.
          By the definition of divides <xref ref="defn_divides"/> we can write <m>n = dk_1</m> and
          <m>n+1 = dk_2</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
          Observe that
          <me>
            (n+1) - n = dk_2 - dk_1 = d(k_2-k_1)
          </me>
          and so <m>d \mid (n+1)-n</m>.
          But, of course, <m>(n+1)-n=1</m> so really <m>d \mid 1</m>.
          Since the only positive divisor of 1 is 1, it follows that <m>d =1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          \st{On the other hand, we assumed that <m>d \neq 1</m>.
          This is a contradiction.
          Thus <m>\fn{gcd}(n,n+1)=1</m>.}
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_and_or">for</xref> \subandor</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_standard_truthtables">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Copy the standard truth tables for each expression.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \land Q</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \lor Q</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \oplus Q</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_translate_into_and_or">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For this exercise, <m>n</m> is a specific
            (but unknown)
            integer, <m>X=</m> <m>n</m> is a multiple of 6, and <m>R=</m> <m>n</m> is a multiple of 4.
            In each part of this exercise write the statement using <m>X</m>,
            <m>R</m>,
            and logic symbols and find an example of an integer <m>n</m> for which the statement is true.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The integer <m>n</m> is a multiple 6 and a multiple of 4.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The integer <m>n</m> is a multiple of exactly one of 6 or 4.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise>
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Recall that a graph is a <term>tree</term>
            if it is connected and acyclic.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Give an example of a tree and explain what you have checked.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Could a graph be connected but not a tree?
                  Give an example and explain in words.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Could a graph be acyclic but not a tree?
                  Give an example and explain in words.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_not_assoc">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_not_assoc">
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for the compound statement <m>P \lor (Q \land R)</m>.
                  Include an intermediate column for <m>Q \land R</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Compare your answer from <xref ref="part_not_assoc"/> with the completed truth table from <xref ref="act_truthtable_and_or"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_finish_truthtable"/>.
                  Is <m>P \lor (Q \land R) \equiv (P \lor Q) \land R</m>?
                  Explain.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_distributive">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for <m>P \land (Q \lor R)</m>.
                  Include an intermediate column for <m>Q \lor R</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for <m>(P \land Q) \lor (P \land R)</m>.
                  Include intermediate columns for
                  <m>P \land Q</m> and for <m>P \land R</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What do you notice?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_and_or">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the symbols <m>\land</m>,
                  <m>\lor</m>, and <m>\oplus</m> stand for?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the logical connectives
                  <q>and</q>,
                  <q>or</q>, and
                  <q>xor</q>
                  mean?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When statements of the form <m>P \land Q</m> and
                  <m>P \lor Q</m> are true and when they're false?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why we might create a truth table?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to create a truth table for a compound logical statement?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_and_or">for</xref> \subpffandor</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_odd_and_mult3">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_and">Use</xref> to prove that 12 is even and <m>3 \mid 12</m>.
            Hint: Copy the proof in <xref ref="act_prove_and_orusingcases"></xref>
            <xref ref="part_pff_and_example"/> and edit as needed.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_nsqplusn_mod4">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_or_by_cases">Use</xref>
            to to prove that <m>n^2+2n \fn{ mod } 4 = 0</m> or
            <m>n^2+2n \fn{ mod } 4 = 3</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
            Hint: Copy the proof in <xref ref="act_prove_and_orusingcases"></xref>
            <xref ref="part_pff_or_using_cases_example"/> and edit as needed.
            Yes, this exercise <xref ref="act_prove_and_orusingcases">repeats</xref>
            <xref ref="part_nsqplusn_mod4"/>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_odd_and_mult3_general">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_and">Use</xref> to prove that <m>3n+6</m> is even and
            <m>3 \mid (3n+6)</m> for any integer <m>n</m>.
            Hint: Copy the proof in <xref ref="act_prove_and_orusingcases"></xref>
            <xref ref="part_pff_and_example"/> and edit as needed.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sq_mod5">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use Proof <xref ref="pff_or_by_cases_generalized">Format</xref>
            to prove that for any integer <m>n</m> we have <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 5 = 0</m>,
            <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 5 = 1</m>, or <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 5 = 4</m>.
            Hint: By the Division Algorithm
            <m>n = 5q+r</m> with <m>0 \le r \lt 5</m>.
            Break into five cases corresponding to <m>r=0, 1, 2, 3</m>,
            or <m>4</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pff_and_or_by_cases">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How we prove a statement of the form <m>P \land Q</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How we prove a statement of the form <m>P \lor Q</m> using cases?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_logical_equivalence_negations">for</xref>
      \subequivneg</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_my_first_negate">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Negate each statement about an integer <m>k</m>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>k=10</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>k>10</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>k</m> is odd
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>10 \mid k</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_my_first_demorgans">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Negate each statement about the integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            Hint: Use DeMorgan's Laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/> and <xref ref="rem_but_not"></xref>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>a</m> is even and <m>b</m> is even
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>a</m> is even but <m>b</m> is odd
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_translate_into_and_or_with_not">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For this exercise, <m>n</m> is a specific
            (but unknown)
            integer, <m>X=</m> <m>n</m> is a multiple of 6, and <m>R=</m> <m>n</m> is a multiple of 4.
            In each part of this exercise write the statement using <m>X</m>,
            <m>R</m>,
            and logic symbols and find an example of an integer <m>n</m> for which the statement is true.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The integer <m>n</m> is not a multiple of 6.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The integer <m>n</m> is a multiple of 6, but not a multiple of 4.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The integer <m>n</m> is a multiple of 4, but not a multiple of 6.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The integer <m>n</m> is not a multiple of 4 or 6.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_andornot">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use a truth table to show that <m>P \lor \neg P</m> is a tautology.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Draw a truth table for <m>P \lor \neg Q</m>.
                  Include an intermediate column for <m>\neg Q</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Draw a truth table for <m>\neg P \land Q</m>.
                  Include an intermediate column for <m>\neg P</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_demorgan">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="act_not_and">In</xref>
            we verified the first of De Morgan's Laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/>.
            Construct truth tables to verify the second equivalence
            <me>
              \neg(P \lor Q) \equiv \neg P \land \neg Q
            </me>.
            Include some intermediate columns.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_equiv_negation">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What it means for statements to be logically equivalent and how we might use a truth table to verify an equivalence?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What a tautology or contradiction is and how to verify that a statement is a tautology or contradiction using a truth table.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the negation of a statement is?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the symbols <m>\neg</m> and <m>\equiv</m> mean?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How the construction <m>\land \neg</m> is translated into words.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to find the negation of <m>P \land Q</m> and
                  <m>P \lor Q</m> and what those equivalences are called?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_writing_xor_without_xor">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find a statement that is logically equivalent to
                  <m>P \oplus Q</m> but does not use <m>\oplus</m>.
                  You may use <m>\land</m>, <m>\lor</m>,
                  <m>\neg</m>, and parentheses.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use a truth table to verify that the statements are equivalent.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is the negation of the statement <m>P \oplus Q</m>?
                  Describe the negation using <m>\land</m>,
                  <m>\lor</m>, and <m>\neg</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_contra">for</xref> \subpffcontra</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_not_sum_3digits_equals25">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/> to prove that there do not exist three distinct digits whose sum is equal to 25.
            This statement was one of the true/false questions in <xref ref="act_TorF"></xref>
            <xref ref="part_digit_sum25"/>.
            Hint: The negation would be that there exist three distinct digits whose sum is 25.
            What is the largest possible set of three distinct digits and what is their sum?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_contradiction_coins_in_cups">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            We have nine coins and four cups.
            We place each coin in a cup.
            <xref ref="pff_contradiction">Use</xref>
            to prove that some cup has three or more coins.
            Hint: The negation would be that each cup has two or fewer coins.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_contradiction_3reg_graph_order7">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/> to prove that there cannot exist a 3-regular graph of order 7.
            Hint: <xref ref="thm_first_thm_graph_thy">By</xref>,
            the number of edges in a graph is equal to half of the sum of the degrees of the vertices.
            On the other hand, the number of edges must be an integer.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_bs_length5_three0s_or_three1s">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use a proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/> to prove that every bit string of length five has at least three <c>0</c> s or at least three <c>1</c> s.
                  Hint: The negation would be that there exists a bit string of length five with fewer than three <m>\bs{0}</m>s and fewer than three <m>\bs{1}</m>s.
                  What is the longest such possible bit string?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why does the negation use
                  <q>and</q>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_contradiction_coprime">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are coprime integers and <m>p</m> is a positive prime.
            Use a proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/> to prove that <m>p \nmid a</m> or <m>p \nmid b</m>.
            Hint: Be careful negating the
            <q>or</q>
            statement.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pff_contradiction">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why <m>Q \land \neg Q</m> is a contradiction?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to write a proof by contradiction?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How we can begin a proof by contradiction so the reader knows that we are doing a proof by contradiction?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why the phrase
                  <q>On the other hand</q>
                  is used in a proof by contradiction?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_not_both_even_odd">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a proof by contradiction <xref ref="pff_contradiction"/> to prove that an integer <m>n</m> cannot be even and odd.
            Hint: If <m>n</m> is even,
            use the definition of even to write <m>n = 2k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
            If <m>n</m> is odd,
            use the definition of odd to write <m>n=2q+1</m> for some integer <m>q</m>.
            Do not use <m>k</m> again.
            Put these equations together to get <m>2k=2q+1</m>.
            Next, solve for 1 to show that <m>2 \mid 1</m>.
            On the other hand, the only divisors of 1 are <m>\pm1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_lg3_irrat">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Copy the following proof and fill in the blanks.<fn>
            Thanks to Oscar Levin for the idea for this exercise.
            </fn>
          </p>
          <p>
            Prove that <m>\fn{lg}(3)</m> is irrational.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose not.
            Then <m>\fn{lg}(3)</m> is <fillin/>.
            By the definition of rational numbers <xref ref="defn_fraction_rational"/>, we can write
            <me>
              \fn{lg}(3) = \frac{s}{t}
            </me>
            for some integers <m>s</m> and <m>t</m> with <m>t \neq 0</m>.
            Using the definition of <c>lg</c> <xref ref="defn_log"/>, we can write
            <me>
              2^{^{\frac{s}{t}}} = \underline{\hspace{.5 in}}
            </me>.
            Raising both sides of this equation to the power <m>t</m> we get
            <me>
              2^s = \underline{\hspace{.5 in}}
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            On the other hand,
            any power of two is even and so <fillin/> is even and any power of three is odd and so <fillin/> is odd.
            <xref ref="exer_not_both_even_odd">By</xref>,
            an integer cannot be even and odd.
            Thus,
            <me>
              2^s \neq \underline{\hspace{.5 in}}
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            This is a contradiction.
            Thus, <m>\fn{lg}(3)</m> is irrational.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_inf_many_primes">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> Copy the following proof and fill in the blanks.
          </p>
          <p>
            Prove that there are infinitely many primes.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose not.
            Then there would be a <fillin/> number of primes,
            so we could list all of them.
            Suppose that the list of all primes were <m>p_1,p_2,p_3, \ldots,p_k</m>.
            Consider the positive integer
            <me>
              n = p_1p_2p_3\cdots p_k
            </me>
          </p>
          <p>
            First, <m>n = p_1(p_2p_3\cdots p_k)</m> so by the definition of
            <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m> it follows that <m>p_1 \mid n</m>.
            Since <m>p_1</m> is prime, we know that <m>p_1 > 1</m>.
            <xref ref="exer_consec_coprime">By</xref>,
            we know that <m>\fn{gcd}(n,n+1) = \underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
            Since <m>p_1 > 1</m> and <m>p_1 \mid n</m>,
            it follows that <m>p_1 \nmid (n+1)</m>.
            For each value of <m>i = 1, 2, \ldots k</m>,
            the same argument shows that <m>p_i >1</m> and
            <m>p_i \mid n</m> and so <m>p_i \nmid (n+1)</m>.
            Therefore, none of the primes
            <m>p_1,p_2,p_3, \ldots,
            p_k</m> divides <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            On the other hand,
            <m>p_1,p_2,p_3, \ldots,p_k</m> are the only primes.
            It follows that <m>n+1</m> has no prime divisors.
            Since <m>n</m> is positive, we know <m>n+1>1</m>.
            This is a contraction of <xref ref="thm_FTOArith"></xref>
            which says <m>\underline{\hspace{1in}}</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_translate_into_and_or"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>X \land R</m> which is true when <m>n=12</m>.
            There are other correct examples.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\oplus</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_truthtable_distributive"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="part_truthtable_dist1">
          <p>
            <xref ref="table_truthtable_dist1">See</xref>.
            <table xml:id="table_truthtable_dist1">
              <title>Truth table for the compound statement <m>P \land (Q \lor R)</m></title>
              <tabular>
                <row>
                  <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>R</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>Q \lor R</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>P \land (Q \lor R)</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                  <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: You should get the same final column as in <xref ref="part_truthtable_dist1"/>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            They are logically equivalent.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_odd_and_mult3"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: <m>12 = 2(6)</m> and <m>12 = 3(4)</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_nsqplusn_mod4"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint:
        <me>
          (2k)^2+2(2k) = 4k^2+4k = 4(\underline{\hspace{.5in}}) + 0
        </me>
        and
        <me>
          (2k+1)^2 + 2(2k+1) = 4k^2 + 8k + 3= 4(\underline{\hspace{.5in}}) + 3
        </me>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_odd_and_mult3_general"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Make sure to copy all the words in the proof.
        During the proof, you will need to write
        <m>3n+6 = 2(\underline{\hspace{.5in}})</m> and <m>3n+6 = 3(\underline{\hspace{.5in}})</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sq_mod5"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The five cases are Case 1: Assume <m>n = 5q</m>; Case 2: Assume <m>n=5q+1</m>; Case 3: Assume <m>n=5q+2</m>; Case 4: Assume <m>n=5q+3</m>;
        and Case 5: Assume <m>n=5q+4</m>.
        In Case 4, for example, we have
        <me>
          n^2=(5q+3)^2=25q^2+30q+9=25q^2+30q+5+4=5(5q^2+6q+1)+4
        </me>
        and so <m>n^2 \fn{ mod } 5 = 4</m>.
        Notice how we cleverly rewrite <m>9 = 5+4</m>.
        That made it possible to factor 5 out of the 5 to show the remainder of 4.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_my_first_negate"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>k \neq 10</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Make sure your answer includes the possibility that <m>k=10</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>k</m> is even.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Use <m>\nmid</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
