    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prove_not_sum_3digits_equals25"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Copy this proof filling in the missing parts.
      </p>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Suppose not.
          Then there exist three distinct digits whose sum is equal to 25.
        </p>
        <p>
          On the other hand,
          the largest possible set of three distinct digits is
          <m>\{ \underline{\hspace{.1in}}, \underline{\hspace{.1in}}, \underline{\hspace{.1in}}\}</m> and their sum is <m>\underline{\hspace{.1in}} + \underline{\hspace{.1in}}+\underline{\hspace{.1in}}=\underline{\hspace{.1in}} \neq 25</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is a contradiction.
          Therefore, there do not exist three distinct digits whose sum is equal to 25.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_contradiction_3reg_graph_order7"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: If there were such a graph,
        the sum of the degrees of the vertices would be
        <me>
          3+3+3+3+3+3+3=7(3)=21
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then, use the hint.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
